      • SortedVector

        public SortedVector(java.util.Collection<? extends E> collection,
            java.util.Comparator<E> comparator)
        Constructor
        Constructs a vector containing the elements of the specified collection. The quick sort algorithm is used to ensure ascending order according to the Comparator.
        Parameters:
        collection - the Collection whose elements are to be placed into this SortedVector
        comparator - the Comparator to use with binary search algorithm
        Complexity:
        Average case: O(n log n), where n is this container's size (QuickSort complexity)

    • Method Detail

      • insertSorted

        public boolean insertSorted(E element)
        Insert an element into the vector, sorted in ascending order according to the Comparator. The binary search algorithm is used to determine the position, where the object should be inserted.
        Parameters:
        element - the element to insert
        Returns:
        TRUE, iff the element was successfully inserted. FALSE, if the element could not be inserted, e.g. if the vector was already holding an equal element according to the Comparator
        Complexity:
        Average/worst case: O(log n), where n is this container's size (BinarySearch complexity)
        Postcondition:
        The underlying container is still sorted in ascending order according to the Comparator after the specified Object has been inserted.

      • insertSorted

        public boolean insertSorted(E... elements)
        Insert elements into the vector, sorted in ascending order according to the Comparator. The binary search algorithm is used to determine the position, where the object should be inserted.
        Parameters:
        elements - the elements to insert
        Returns:
        TRUE, iff the elements was successfully inserted. FALSE, if the elements could not be inserted, e.g. if the vector was already holding one or more equal elements according to the Comparator
        Complexity:
        Average/worst case: O(log n), where n is this container's size (BinarySearch complexity)
        Postcondition:
        The underlying container is still sorted in ascending order according to the Comparator after the specified Object has been inserted.

      • binarySearch

        public int binarySearch(E element)
        Standard implementation of binary search algorithm.
        Parameters:
        element - the Object to look for
        Complexity:
        Average/worst case: O(log n), where n is this container's size
        Precondition:
        The underlying container has to be sorted in ascending order according to the Comparator for binary search to work correctly.

      • max

        public static <T extends java.lang.Object & java.lang.Comparable<? super T>> T max(SortedVector<? extends T> data)
        Returns the maximum element of the given sorted vector, according to the natural ordering of its elements. All elements in the sorted vector must implement the Comparable interface. Furthermore, all elements in the sorted vector must be mutually comparable (that is, e1.compareTo(e2) must not throw a ClassCastException for any elements e1 and e2 in the sorted vector).
        Parameters:
        data - the SortedVector whose maximum element is to be determined
        Returns:
        the maximum element of the given sorted vector, according to the natural ordering of its elements.
